I expect the true diabetes‐ever prevalence in this heavy, lead‐exposed subgroup to be above the overall adult rate (~10%), likely around 15 %.  A Beta prior is natural for a probability on [0,1].

•  Range:  I’m quite sure the rate is above ~9 % (the overweight/obese baseline) and below ~22 %;  
•  Center:  about 15 %, since weight >94.5 kg selects overweight/obese adults (CDC reports ~12–13 %), while higher lead may modestly increase risk;  
•  Uncertainty:  moderate – I capture this with a 95 % credible interval ≈[0.092, 0.216];  
•  Beta(20,110) gives mean=20/130≈0.1538 and var≈0.0010 ⇒ sd≈0.032 ⇒ 95 % CI≈0.154±1.96·0.032≈[0.092, 0.216].  

Beta is appropriate because it models a probability and these α, β reflect our uncertainty about the subgroup prevalence (not individual variation).

